ndata\\ndata_bridge.py\\ndata_quality.py\\nexport_features.py\\nfeatures_view.sql\\nintegration_test.py\\nnfp_pipeline.py\\noutput\\nREADME.md\\nrequirements.txt\\nrun.sh\\nRUNBOOK.md\\nsample_data_loader.py\\nschema.sql\\nsignal_adapter.py\",\"stderr\":\"\",\"interrupted\":false,\"isImage\":false,\"noOutputExpected\":false}}\n./logs/2026_04_03_raw.log:67:{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01DoyR4tv7nXkU8tDYQxuLcA\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"Now I have a good understanding of the trading pipeline. Let me write the cloud deployment plan. The pipeline consists of:\\n\\n1. **Node.js backend** (`agents/bob/backend/`) with:\\n   - Kalshi API client\\n   - Strategy runner (mean_reversion primary strategy)\\n   - PostgreSQL database\\n   - Express API server\\n   - Scheduler (run every 10 minutes via `run_scheduler.sh` + `live_runner.js`)\\n\\n2. **Dashboard** (`server.js`) on port 3199\\n   - SQLite for agent state\\n   - Volume-mounted agent state\\n\\nThe key environment variables I need to configure are the Kalshi API credentials, dashboard authentication keys, the paper vs live trading flag, and the dashboard port. The project already has Docker and docker-compose set up for the dashboard, so I'll design an AWS deployment using ECS Fargate for container orchestration and RDS for the PostgreSQL database to avoid managing infrastructure myself.\\n\\nFor the scheduler, I can replace the bash while loop with EventBridge, store API keys securely in Secrets Manager, and use CloudWatch for monitoring. But honestly, the most practical approach for a single person to deploy in a day would be simpler—just run Docker Compose on a single EC2 t3.small instance, optionally add RDS PostgreSQL for the trading database, and use Secrets Manager and CloudWatch for configuration and logging.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"stop_details\"